	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Expansion of sustainability labelling schemes continues</h1>

			
			<h4>
												04 March 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to a report published in January by Organic Monitor, a marketing and information services company, ‘the number of eco-labels in the food industry is expected to continue to proliferate in 2013.’ This is attributed to ‘growing consumer awareness of food production methods and sustainability issues’. However, there are concerns that food producers could be discouraged from using sustainability labels as a result of a growing disparity between the value of individual labels and the increase in certification costs. There are also concerns that the multiplication of sustainability labels is potentially confusing consumers and undermining the value of such labels.</p><p>The report notes that ‘the majority of eco-labels in the food industry are for organic products, which are made according to the most sustainable form of agriculture.’ While the bulk of organic products are sold in the EU and US, ‘many new organic labels are being introduced in Asia, Latin America and other regions.’ Indeed, ‘over 84 countries have introduced national standards for organic products.’ There is, however, a ‘lack of harmonisation between these standards’, which is leading to multiple certification requirements.</p><p>Fair-trade certification processes are also fragmenting, with, for example, ‘the departure of Fair Trade USA from the umbrella organisation’. The report notes that the ‘growing number of new fair trade schemes [is] increasing the number of fair trade logos and symbols’.</p><p>While the Rainforest Alliance and UTZ Certified have a well-established role in sustainability certification for products such as cocoa, coffee and teas, ‘new schemes are gaining popularity for such commodities’, including Bird Friendly Coffee and Starbuck’s Coffee and Farmer Equity (CAFE) practices. In addition, new labels are emerging on specific aspects of sustainability, such as carbon labelling and ‘water footprint’ labelling schemes.</p><p>As a result, Organic Monitor notes, ‘a wider question is whether a new umbrella eco-label will eventually emerge and unify existing ones.’</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><i>Organic Monitor</i>, ‘2013: Proliferation of food eco-labels to continue’, 16 January 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.organic-market.info/web/News_in_brief/North_America/eco-labels/176/328/0/13877.html" target="_self">http://www.organic-market.info/web/News_in_brief/North_America/eco-label...</a></p><p>Global Social Compliance Programme, website</p><p>
<a href="http://www.gscpnet.com/" target="_self">http://www.gscpnet.com/</a></p><p>International Federation of Organic Agriculture Movements (IFOAM), website</p><p>
<a href="http://www.ifoam.org/about_ifoam/index.html" target="_self">http://www.ifoam.org/about_ifoam/index.html</a></p><p><i>Organic Monitor</i>, ‘Organic milk exports to China’, 14 November 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://www.organicmonitor.com/europe.htm" target="_self">http://www.organicmonitor.com/europe.htm</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The continuing proliferation of sustainability labelling initiatives gives added importance to efforts to promote mutual recognition of audit processes linked to sustainability certification. Initiatives supported by the Global Social Compliance Programme (GSCP), such as the Sustainability Initiative of South Africa, would appear to be particularly relevant in this regard. Scope may exist for extending such initiatives regionally, first within SADC, and then within SADC and the proposed Tripartite FTA. This is potentially an area for ‘aid for trade’ support.</p><p>However, with organic labelling leading the way in terms of market penetration, important public policy issues arise with regard to harmonising mutual recognition procedures across regulatory bodies. This is another important potential area for ‘aid for trade’ support to ACP countries, where many governments are starting from scratch in defining national regulatory frameworks for organic production.</p><p>The current EU practice of concluding bilateral mutual recognition agreements for organic standards risks marginalising ACP countries from the growing trade in organic products, since exporters without an equivalency agreement will face higher administrative costs in certifying compliance with EU organic standards, and development which will further compound challenges of economies of scale linked to certification.</p><p>Individual ACP markets are in general too small to be of interest to European organic exporters, hence interest on the EU side in concluding mutual recognition agreements on the equivalence of organic standards is likely to be minimal. China would seem to be a much greater priority for concluding mutual recognition agreements on standards, with even exports of organic milk from Denmark to China scheduled to commence in the spring of 2013.</p><p>This is potentially an area for a joint ACP initiative to establish a common framework for securing mutual recognition of organic standards, possibly in collaboration with the International Federation of Organic Agriculture Movements (IFOAM).</p>
		</div>
		
